1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:10,859
Welcome back.

2
00:00:10,859 --> 00:00:15,939
This module we are going to talk about basic natural language processing and how it relates

3
00:00:15,939 --> 00:00:20,859
to the text mining in Python that we have been talking about.

4
00:00:20,859 --> 00:00:22,859
So what is natural language?

5
00:00:22,859 --> 00:00:28,640
Well any language that is used in everyday communication by humans is natural language.

6
00:00:28,640 --> 00:00:35,200
Let's compare to something that is artificial language or a computer language like Python.

7
00:00:35,200 --> 00:00:40,719
Languages such as English or Chinese or Hindi or Russian or Spanish are all natural languages

8
00:00:40,719 --> 00:00:48,200
but you know also the language we use in short text messages or on tweets is also by this

9
00:00:48,200 --> 00:00:51,240
definition natural language isn't it?

10
00:00:51,240 --> 00:00:54,920
So then we have to kind of address these as well.

11
00:00:54,920 --> 00:00:57,200
So then what is natural language processing?

12
00:00:57,200 --> 00:01:03,680
Any computation or manipulation of natural language to get some insights about how words

13
00:01:03,680 --> 00:01:10,120
mean and how sentences are constructed is natural language processing.

14
00:01:10,120 --> 00:01:15,480
One thing to consider when we look at natural language is that these evolve.

15
00:01:15,480 --> 00:01:21,520
For example new words get added like selfie or photobomb.

16
00:01:21,520 --> 00:01:24,079
Old words lose popularity.

17
00:01:24,079 --> 00:01:27,159
How often have you used thou shalt?

18
00:01:27,200 --> 00:01:29,959
Meaning of words change.

19
00:01:29,959 --> 00:01:34,679
Words such as learn in old English meant exactly opposite of what it means now.

20
00:01:34,679 --> 00:01:37,000
It used to mean teach.

21
00:01:37,000 --> 00:01:39,959
And then language rules themselves may change.

22
00:01:39,959 --> 00:01:44,599
So for example in old English the position of the verb was at the end of the sentence rather

23
00:01:44,599 --> 00:01:48,640
than the middle as we come to know today.

24
00:01:48,640 --> 00:01:53,679
So when we talk about NLP tasks what do we mean?

25
00:01:53,680 --> 00:01:59,040
It could mean as simple as counting the words or counting the frequency of a word or

26
00:01:59,040 --> 00:02:01,880
finding unique words in a corpus.

27
00:02:01,880 --> 00:02:07,760
And then build on to find sentence boundaries or parts of speech.

28
00:02:07,760 --> 00:02:12,159
So tag a sentence with its parts of speech.

29
00:02:12,159 --> 00:02:13,960
Pass the sentence structure.

30
00:02:13,960 --> 00:02:20,360
Try to understand more grammatical constructs and see whether they apply for a particular sentence.

31
00:02:20,760 --> 00:02:24,320
Identify semantic roles of how these words play.

32
00:02:24,320 --> 00:02:33,200
For example if you have a sentence like Mary loves John then you know that Mary is the subject.

33
00:02:33,200 --> 00:02:39,320
John is the object and love is the verb that connects them.

34
00:02:39,320 --> 00:02:45,120
You have the other NLP tasks like identifying entities in a sentence.

35
00:02:45,120 --> 00:02:47,880
So this is called named entity recognition.

36
00:02:47,919 --> 00:02:58,039
And in our previous example of Mary loves John, Mary and John are the two entities, both persons in that sentence.

37
00:02:58,039 --> 00:03:08,400
And then you could have more complicated, more complex tasks like finding which pronoun refers to which entity.

38
00:03:08,400 --> 00:03:12,560
This is called co-reference resolution or co-reference resolution.

39
00:03:12,560 --> 00:03:19,000
And there are many, many more tasks that you would do on free text.

40
00:03:19,000 --> 00:03:26,599
The challenge is how to do that in an efficient manner and how it applies to overall text mining.

41
00:03:26,599 --> 00:03:30,319
And you're going to see some of those in the next few videos.

